In article <1sgt9l$erp@transfer.stratus.com> cme@ellisun.sw.stratus.com (Carl Ellison) writes:
   /dev/audio with nothing connected) and self-encrypt it:
	   cat /dev/audio|compress -|des|tran|des|tran|des >file

   Of course, for crypto purposes, having random numbers around in a
   file weakens their security....

That's relatively easy to fix, on a Sun:
	cat /dev/audio|compress -|des|tran|des|tran|des > /dev/fd0
To copy it, you need to write a simple program that reads the floppy
disk into memory, prompts the user to insert a new floppy, and writes
out the data onto the floppy, and ideally locks itself into physical
memory to avoid swapping.
